\p
\v 59 \add Another group\add* went from \add the towns of\add* Tel-Melah, Tel-Harsha, Keruv, Addon, and Immer, \add but\add* they \add didn’t know their ancestry\add* \add from before they were taken as captives\add*.
\p
\v 60 There were 652 people who were descendants of Delayah, Toviyyah, and Nekoda,
\v 61 and from the sons of the priests: the descendants of Havayyah; the descendants of Hakkots; and the descendants of Barzillai, who took a wife from the daughters of Barzillai the Gileadite, so he was called by their name.
\v 62 \add They\add* had searched for their \add records\add* among the \add genealogies\add*, but \add couldn’t find\add* \add their families listed\add*, \add so\add* they were \add disqualified to serve as priests\add*.
\v 63 \add Also\add* the governor told them that they mustn’t eat any of the holiest food until a priest \add could use the Urim and Thummim\add* \add to determine their status\add*.\x + \xo 2:63: \xt Num 27:21.\x*
\p
\v 64 \add Altogether in this group\add*, 42,360 people \add returned to Yehudah\add*.
\v 65 \add not counting\add* their 7,337 male and female servants, plus 200 male and female musicians.
\v 66 \add They also took\add* 736 horses and 245 mules,
\v 67 435 camels and 6,720 donkeys.
\p
\v 68 When some of the \add heads of families\add* got to Yahweh’s temple in Yerushalem, they freely donated \add so that it could be rebuilt\add*.
\v 69 They each donated to the treasury according to \add their individual resources\add*—\add a total of\add* sixty-one thousand gold coins, five thousand silver bars, and a hundred sets of clothing for the priests.
\p
\v 70 \add So\add* the priests and the Levites, and some of the people, and the singers, and the gatekeepers and the temple servants \add returned to\add* live in their \add ancestral\add* cities, and \add so\add* all the Israeli cities \add had returnees living in them\add*.\x + \xo 2:70: \xt 1Ch 9:2; Neh 11:3.\x*
\c 3
\s1 Rebuilding the altar
\p
\v 1 In the seventh month, the Israelis from their \add various\add* cities, gathered together \add in unity\add* in Yerushalem.
\v 2 Then Yotsadak’s son Yeshua and his brothers the priests, and Shealti’el’s son Zerubavel and his brothers, and they built the altar to offer up burnt offerings to Israel’s God on it as is written in the law of Mosheh, the man of God.\x + \xo 3:2: \xt Exo 27:1.\x*
\v 3 They set the altar up on its foundation because they were worried \add about trouble from\add* some of the \add other\add* people groups \add in the region\add*. Then they offered burnt offerings to Yahweh on it \add as well as the regular\add* morning and evening burnt offerings.\x + \xo 3:3: \xt Num 28:1-8.\x*
\v 4 Then they observed the Celebration in Shelters as \add per the written instructions\add*\x + \xo 3:4: \xt Num 29:12-38.\x* with a burnt offering each day as required.
\v 5 After that \add was over\add*, they kept up the regular burnt offerings, plus those for the new moons and other times that Yahweh required, as well as any free-will offerings to Yahweh.\x + \xo 3:5: \xt Num 28:11–29:39.\x*
\v 6 \add Even though the temple foundation rebuilding hadn’t started yet\add*, the people started sacrificing burnt offerings to Yahweh \add from the beginning of October\add*.
\s1 Rebuilding the temple
\p
\v 7 They donated cash to the stone-workers and carpenters, and food, drink, and oil to the workers from Tsidon \add (Sidon)\add* and Tsor \add (Tyre)\add* to \add float\add* cedar \add logs along the coast\add* from Lebananon into Port Yafo \add (Joppa)\add* with the permission of Persian King Koresh \add (Cyrus)\add*.
\p
\v 8 In the second month of second year \add since their return to\add* Yerushalem, Shealtiel’s son Zerubavel and Yotsadak’s son Yeshua, and the rest of their brothers the priests and the Levites, and \add everyone except who’d returned\add* to Yerushalem from captivity, began work on God’s residence, and they appointed the Levites who were twenty and over to act as overseers for the work of \add rebuilding\add* Yahweh’s \add temple\add*.
\v 9 \add And\add* Yeshua with his brothers and their sons, Kadmiel and his sons, (all descendants of Yehudah) \add cooperated\add* to act as overseers for those doing the work at the \add temple\add* \add together with\add* Henadad’s sons \add and grandsons\add*, and their brothers the Levites.
\p
\v 10 \add When the builders had\add* laid the foundation of Yahweh’s temple, they \add got\add* the priests \add to stand there in their robes\add* with their trumpets, and Asaf’s descendants (who were Levites) with their cymbals, to praise Yahweh \add using the rhythms composed by\add* David, the \add former\add* Israeli king.\x + \xo 3:10: \xt 1Ch 25:1.\x*
\v 11 Then they sang in response—praising and thanking Yahweh: “\add Yes,\add* he is good, because his loyal commitment to Israel \add will continue forever\add*.”
\p Then all the people shouted a great shout in praise to Yahweh because the foundation of Yahweh’s \add temple\add* had been laid.\x + \xo 3:11: \xt 1Ch 16:34; 2Ch 5:13; 7:3; Psa 100:5; 106:1; 107:1; 118:1; 136:1; Jer 33:11.\x*
\v 12 Many of the older priests and Levites, and \add clan leaders\add* who’d seen the first \add temple\add*, wept loudly \add when they witnessed\add* the founding of this \add one\add*, \add but others were shouting happily with loud voices\add*.
\v 13 So the people couldn’t differentiate the happy sounds from the sound of the people weeping, because the people were shouting \add very loudly and it could be heard from far away\add*.
\c 4
\s1 Opposition to rebuilding the temple
\p
\v 1 \add Now\add* the enemies of Yehudah and Benyamin heard that the \add Israelis who’d come back from\add* exile were building a temple for Israel’s God Yahweh.
\v 2 \add so\add* they went to Zerubavel and to the \add other\add* \add clan leaders\add* and they said to them, “Let us \add help you with the building work\add*, because like you, we \add worship\add* your God and we’ve been sacrificing to him since the days of the Assyrian king Esar-Haddon—the one who \add sent\add* us here.”\x + \xo 4:2: \xt 2Ki 17:24-41.\x*
\p
\v 3 \add But\add* Zerubavel, and Yeshua, and the rest of the \add Israelis clan leaders\add* said to them, “It’s not for you and for us to build a house for our God, but we ourselves together will build for Israel’s God Yahweh, just as the Persian King Koresh \add (Cyrus)\add* has commanded us.”
\p
\v 4 \add Those local\add* people had been discouraging the people of Yehudah and trying to stop them from building.
\v 5 They’d \add also\add* hired \add influencers to work against them throughout the reigns\add* of the Persian kings Koresh \add (Cyrus)\add* and Dareyavesh \add (Darius)\add*.
\s1 The opposition of replacement of Yerushalem
\p
\v 6 Now at the beginning of the reign of Ahashverosh \add (Ahasuerus or Xerxes)\add*, they \add forwarded\add* an accusation against those who lived in Yerushalem and \add throughout\add* Yehudah.
\p
\v 7 And in the days of Persian King Artahshasta \add (Artaxerxes)\add*, Bishlam, Mitredat, Taveel and the rest of \add their\add* companions wrote to the king. (The letter was written in Aramaic \add (Syrian)\add* and \add using that alphabet\add*).
\p
\v 8 Rehum \add the high commissioner\add* and Shimshai the \add provincial secretary\add* wrote a letter to King Artahshasta against Yerushalem as follows:
\p
\v 9 \add From\add* Rehum \add the high commissioner\add* and Shimshai the \add provincial secretary\add*, and the \add our\add* companions, the judges and the rulers, the officials, the Persians, the Erechites, the Babylonians, the Susaites (that is, the Elamites),
\v 10 and the rest of the nations that the famous and powerful \add King\add* Asenappar exiled \add from other nations\add* and \add forced\add* them to live in the cities of Samaria, and the \add province went of the Euphrates river\add*.
\p And now
\v 11 this is \add what the letter said\add* that they sent to him:
\p To Artahshasta \add (Artaxerxes)\add* the king \add from\add* your servants \add on this side of\add* the river.
\p And now
\v 12 let it be known to the king that the Jews who \add left your region\add* have come to us at Yerushalem \add to\add* rebuild that rebellious and evil city—they’re \add currently\add* finishing the walls and repairing the \add building\add* foundations.
\v 13 Now let it be known to the king that if that city is built and the walls are completed, \add those people\add* won’t \add pay\add* \add taxes\add*, \add or send\add* \add tributes\add*, and \add your royal treasury will lose out\add*.
\v 14 Now, because we’ve \add had the favour\add* of the palace, and \add because we don’t want to see the king dishonoured\add*, \add that’s why we’ve sent this letter to update\add* the king,
\v 15 so that he can search in the \add official records of the kingdom\add*. You’ll discover and learn that that city \add of Yerushalem\add* is a rebellious city and one that has caused harm to kings and provinces, and \add has harboured rebellion there for decades past\add*—\add that’s why\add* that city was destroyed.
\v 16 We are letting the king know that if that city is \add rebuilt\add* and its walls are completed, \add then you’ll lose control of this province on this side of the Euphrates\add*.”
\p
\v 17 The king sent this reply:
\p “To Rehum \add the high commissioner\add* and Shimshai \add the provincial secretary\add*, and the rest of their companions who live in Shomron \add (Samaria)\add*, and the rest of \add the people in the province west of the Euphrates\add*: Peace.
\p And now
\v 18 the letter that you all sent to us has been carefully read aloud to me.
\v 19 \add I ordered my officials to search\add* \add the records\add* and discovered \add that it’s true\add* that that city has been \add rebellious and seditious\add* since ancient times.
\v 20 Powerful kings have \add reigned from\add* Yerushalem and ruled the entire region that side of the river, and had taxes and tributes paid to them.
\v 21 \add So command those Jews to stop rebuilding\add* the city until \add such time as I make\add* a decree.
\v 22 \add Don’t be negligent in doing that or the damage to this kingdom might get worse\add*.”
\p
\v 23 When King Artahshasta’s letter \add reached\add* Rehum, Shimshai the \add secretary\add*, and their companions, and was read aloud to them all, they \add immediately\add* went to Yerushalem and \add used force to stop\add* the Jews \add from their rebuilding\add*.
\p
\v 24 \add So there was a period when the rebuilding of the temple in Yerushalem stopped\add*, and it \add remained paused\add* until the second year of King Dareyavesh’s reign in Persia.\x + \xo 4:24: \xt Hag 1:1; Zech 1:1.\x*
\c 5
\s1 The temple rebuilding continues
\p
\v 1 Then the prophet Haggai and Iddo’s son Zecharyah prophesied to the Jews in Yerushalem and \add across\add* Yehudah in the name of Israel’s God \add who they served\add*.\x + \xo 5:1: \xt Hag 1:1; Zech 1:1.\x*
\v 2 Then Shealtiel’s son Zerubbabel and Yotsadak’s son Yeshua \add took action\add* and began to \add rebuild\add* God’s \add temple\add* in Yerushalem, and the prophets \add who served\add* God were \add there\add* with them, supporting them.\x + \xo 5:2: \xt Hag 1:12; Zech 4:6-9.\x*
\p
\v 3 At that time, Tattenai, the governor of \add the province west of the Euphrates\add*, and Shetar-Bozenai, and their companions came to them and \add demanded\add*, “Who \add gave you all permission to rebuild this temple\add*?”
\v 4 \add They also asked the Jews to tell them the names of the men who were working\add* on the building.
\v 5 \add However, God was watching over the Jewish leaders\add*, and they weren’t \add actually\add* stopped. \add A report was sent\add* to \add King\add* Dareyavesh, \add then they waited for a response\add*.
\v 6 Tattenai, the governor of \add the province west of the river\add*, and Shetar-Bozenai and his companions, the \add provincial\add* officials, sent the letter to King Dareyavesh \add (Darius)\add*—
\v 7 this is what was written in their report:
\p “To King Dareyavesh. All peace.
\v 8 Let it be known to the king that we went to the province of Yehudah, to the \add temple\add* of the great God, and it is being built with large stones, and timber is being placed in the walls. This work is being done \add to a high standard\add* and \add they’re making good progress\add*.
\p
\v 9 “Then we asked those elders, ‘Who \add gave you all permission to rebuild this temple\add*?’
\v 10 We also asked them their names, so that we could write down the names of \add their leaders\add* to inform you.
\p
\v 11 “This is the answer they \add gave\add* us, ‘We are servants of the God of the heavens and earth, and we are \add rebuilding the temple\add* that was constructed and finished many years \add ago by a famous Israeli\add* king.
\v 12 However, because our ancestors made the God of the heavens angry, he let Babylonian King Nevukadnetstsar (\add Nebuchadnezzar, \add* the Chaldean) \add defeat them\add*, and he destroyed \add that temple\add* and caused the people to be exiled to Babylon.\x + \xo 5:12: \xt 2Ki 25:8-12; 2Ch 36:17-20; Jer 52:12-15.\x*
\v 13 But in the first year \add of the reign of\add* Babylonian King Koresh \add (Cyrus)\add*, \add he\add* made a decree to rebuild this house of God.\x + \xo 5:13: \xt Ezr 1:2-11.\x*
\v 14 \add What’s more,\add* the gold and silver \add containers\add* that Nevukadnetstsar had taken out from that temple that was in Yerushalem and had brought to the temple in Babylon, King Koresh took them out from the temple in Babylon and they were \add handed over\add* to the man named Sheshbatstsar who he’d appointed as governor \add over Yehudah\add*.
\v 15 \add Koresh\add* had told him to take those containers and put them back in the temple in Yerushalem, and \add to ensure that the temple got rebuilt in the same place where it had been before\add*.
\v 16 \add So\add* Sheshbatstsar came \add here\add* and laid the foundation of God’s house in Yerushalem, and since then, it’s been being rebuilt but isn’t finished yet.’
\p
\v 17 \add So\add* now, if it \add pleases\add* the king, let a search be made in \add the records in\add* the king’s treasure house there in Babylon, if it’s \add correct\add* that a decree was set by King Koresh to rebuild this house of God in Yerushalem. Then let the king send his decision on this matter back to us.”
\c 6
\s1 The former approval is found
\p
\v 1 \add So\add* King Dareyavesh \add (Darius)\add* \add ordered that a search be conducted\add* in \add all\add* the \add archives\add* where treasures had been deposited there in Babylon,
\v 2 and one scroll was found in the fortress at Ecbatana in the province of Media, and this \add record had been made\add*:
\p
\v 3 “In year one of Koresh the king, \add he\add* made a decree about the house of God in Yerushalem:
\m ‘Let the house be built in the \add same\add* place where sacrifices were \add made\add*. \add Establish\add* its foundations and \add build it 27m high and 27m wide\add*
\v 4 with three layers of large \add stones\add* and a layer of new timber. \add That should all be paid for from the royal treasury\add*.
\v 5 Also, the gold and silver containers from the house of God that Nevukadnetstsar had taken out from the Yerushalem temple and had brought to Babylon, must be returned to their places in the temple in Yerushalem. \add So\add* you must put them in the house of God.’ ”
\s1 King Dareyavesh orders resumption of work
\p
\v 6 \add Therefore King Dareyavesh wrote:\add* “Now to Governor Tattenai \add in the province west of the Euphrates\add*, Shetar-Bozenai, and their companions, the officials who in that province:
\p \add Keep away from that place\add*.
\v 7 Leave alone the work on that house of God. Let the Jewish governor and elders build that \add temple\add* in its place.
\v 8 \add So here’s my decree about what should be done for\add* those Jewish elders to build that house of God: Using the king’s treasures that come from the tribute of that west-Euphrates province, let \add those workers costs be regularly reimbursed\add* so that \add the work\add* doesn’t stop.
\v 9 Whatever is needed (\add including young\add* bulls, or rams, or lambs for burnt offerings to the God of the heavens, wheat, salt, wine, or oil, according to the command of the priests in Yerushalem), let it be given to them day by day (that is, without delay),
\v 10 so that they can be offering sweet-smelling sacrifices to the God of the heavens and praying for the life of the king and his sons.
\v 11 \add Also I\add* decree that any man who changes this edict should have a beam pulled from his house, and \add after it’s sharpened and\add* \add set into the ground\add*, then he should be impaled on it. Then his \add entire\add* house should be made into a rubbish heap \add because of what he did\add*.
\v 12 May the God who has established his name there overthrow any king or person who \add makes any attempt\add* to change \add this decree or\add* to destroy that house of God in Yerushalem. I, Dareyavesh, have \add made\add* a decree. Let it be done diligently.”
\s1 The temple dedication
\p
\v 13 Then Tattenai, the governor of \add the region west of the Euphrates\add*, Shetar-Bozenai, and their companions \add worked hard to follow the instructions sent by King Dareyavesh\add* \add (Darius)\add*.
\v 14 \add So\add* the Jewish elders \add continued\add* building, and \add they were encouraged\add* by the prophesying of the prophet Haggai and Iddo’s son Zekaryah. \add As a result of the decrees of the Persian kings Koresh, and Dareyavesh and Artahshasta\add*, they \add were able to fulfil God’s decree to rebuild\add* \add the temple\add*.\x + \xo 6:14: a \xt Hag 1:1; \xo b \xt Zech 1:1.\x*
\v 15 The \add rebuilt\add* \add temple\add* was finished in \add mid-March\add* in the sixth year of King Dareyavesh’s reign.
\p
\v 16 Then the \add Israeli people\add*, the priests, and the Levites, and the \add ones that had returned from\add* exile, performed the dedication of this house of God with \add celebrations\add*.
\v 17 \add During\add* the dedication, they offered a hundred bulls, two-hundred rams, and four-hundred lambs, as well as twelve male goats for a sin offering for all Israel (matching the number of the tribes).
\v 18 Then they \add organised\add* the priests to stand in their divisions and the Levites in their sections \add to serve\add* the God who \add resides\add* in Yerushalem, according to the \add instructions written by\add* Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*.
\s1 The Feast of ‘pass-over’ of Messenger
\p
\v 19 \add So the people who’d returned from exile celebrated the ‘pass-over’ in late April\add*.\x + \xo 6:19: \xt Exo 12:1-20.\x*
\v 20 The priests and Levites \add all had to be individually\add* purified, and they slaughtered the \add lambs\add* for all the \add exiles\add* and for their brothers the priests, and for themselves.
\v 21 \add Then all the Israelis ate\add* \add the meal\add*—those who’d returned from the exile and every one who’d separated themselves from the uncleanness of the nations of the land in order to search for Israeli’s God Yahweh.
\v 22 Then they happily enjoyed the Flat Bread Celebration for seven days, because Yahweh had \add made them happy\add*, and had caused the Assyrian king \add to show favour to\add* them, to \add assist their work rebuilding\add* the house of God, the God of Israel.
\c 7
\s1 Ezra arrives in Yerushalem
\p
\v 1 \add Many years later\add* in the reign of Persian King Artahshasta \add (Artaxerxes)\add*, Ezra (son of Serayah, son of Azaryah, son of Hilkiyyah,
\v 2 son of Shallum, son of Tsadok, son of Ahitub,
\v 3 son of Amaryah, son of Azaryah, son of Merayot,
\v 4 son of Zerahiah, son of Uzzi, son of Bukki,
\v 5 son of Avishua, the son of Pinhas, the son of Eleazar, the son of Aharon the head priest)
\v 6 was a skilled \add expert\add* in the law that Israel’s God Yahweh had given through Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*. \add With the favour of his God Yahweh helping\add* \add Ezra\add*, the king had granted all his requests, and he travelled from Babylon \add to Yerushalem\add*.
\v 7 \add Some Israelis, including\add* some priests and Levites, singers and gatekeepers, and some temple servants \add travelled\add* to Yerushalem in the seventh year of Artahshasta’s \add reign\add*.
\v 8-9 They left Babylon on New Year’s Day (in early April) and \add with God’s favour\add* \add on the journey\add*, arrived in Yerushalem exactly four months later
\v 10 because Ezra had made \add a firm resolution\add* to \add study\add* Yahweh’s \add written\add* \add instructions\add*, and to \add carefully\add* \add follow\add* \add them\add*, and to teach \add them\add* in Israel.
\s1 King Artahshasta’s letter to Ezra
\p
\v 11 King Artahshasta \add (Artaxerxes)\add* had given a letter for Ezra the priest and scribe and \add expert\add* in Yahweh’s commands and instructions \add to take with him\add*, \add saying\add*:
\p
\v 12 Artahshasta, the king of kings, to the priest Ezra, the scribe of the law of the God of heavens: Peace.
\p Now,
\v 13 \add I hereby\add* decree that anyone in my kingdom from Israel (including priests and Levites) who freely offers to go to Yerushalem with you, may go.
\v 14 \add You are sent by\add* the king and his seven counsellors to \add determine whether\add* \add the people of\add* Yehudah and Yerushalem \add are following\add* the law of your God which \add you have a copy of\add*.
\v 15 \add You are also\add* to take the gold and silver that the king and his counsellors have freely offered to the God of Israel \add who lives\add* in Jerusalem,
\v 16 along with all the gold and silver that you \add collect\add* all \add across\add* Babylon, along with the freewill \add offerings\add* of the people and the priests who freely give towards the house of God in Yerushalem.
\p
\v 17 \add So then\add* you should diligently \add use those funds\add* to buy bulls, rams, lambs, and \add supplies for\add* their grain offerings and drink offerings, and you should offer them on the altar at the your God’s house in Yerushalem.
\v 18 With \add the remaining funds\add*, you can \add use them for\add* whatever seems good to you and your brothers, according to the will of your God.
\v 19 \add Also, make sure that\add* you deliver all those \add gold and silver\add* containers that were \add handed over\add* to you for use in your God’s house in Yerushalem.
\v 20 \add Anything else that’s\add* needed for the house of your God that \add you need to supply can be provided\add* from the king’s treasuries.
\p
\v 21 And I, King Artahshasta \add make\add* a decree for all the treasurers \add in the province west of\add* the river: that you all diligently help with everything that the priest Ezra (the scribe of the law of the God of the heavens) asks from you all—
\v 22 up to three tonnes of silver, five hundred bushels of wheat, two thousand litres of wine and \add the same amount\add* of olive oil, and \add as much salt as he needs\add*.
\v 23 Everything that the God of the heavens decreed to be done should be done exactly \add as he specified because there’s no good reason to make him angry at\add* the kingdom of the king and his sons?
\v 24 \add Also, it should be made clear\add* that there is no authority to \add extract\add* \add taxes\add* or tribute from any priests or Levites, singers or the gatekeepers, the temple servants or the servants of that house of God.
\p
\v 25 As for you, Ezra, \add use the wisdom that your God has given to you to\add* appoint magistrates and judges who can judge all the people who are in \add that province\add* beyond the river—everyone who know the laws of your God (plus you should teach those who don’t know \add them\add*).
\v 26 Anyone who \add refuses to obey\add* your God’s laws and the king’s laws, \add should receive swift\add* judgment—whether it’s confiscation of goods, or banishment, imprisonment, or \add the death sentence\add*.”
\s1 Ezra praises Yahweh
\p
\v 27 Blessed be Yahweh, the God of our fathers who put it into the king’s heart to honour Yahweh’s house in Yerushalem,
\v 28 and showed me his loyal commitment in \add dealing with\add* the king and his counselors, and all the powerful officials of the king. And as for me, Yahweh my God \add blessed me with\add* \add initiative and\add* \add the strength to carry it out as\add* I gathered some Israeli \add leaders\add* to go \add to Yerushalem\add* with me.
\c 8
\s1 The returning exiles
\p
\v 1 Now these are the \add family\add* heads and their \add descendants by number who\add* who went with me from Babylon \add to Yerushalem\add* in the reign of King Artahshasta \add (Artaxerxes)\add*:
\li1
\v 2 from the descendants of Pinhas: Gershom,
\li1 from the descendants of Itamar: Daniyyel,
\li1 from the descendants of David: Hattush,
\li1
\v 3 from the descendants of Shekanyah \add and\add* Far’osh: Zekaryah and a hundred and fifty \add other\add* men,
\li1
\v 4 from the descendants of Pahat-Moab: Zerahyah’s son Eliehoenai and two hundred \add other\add* men,
\li1
\v 5 from the descendants of Shekanyah: Yahatsiel’s son and three hundred \add other\add* men,
\li1
\v 6 from the descendants of Adin: Yonatan’s son Eved and fifty \add other\add* men,
\li1
\v 7 from the descendants of Eylam: Atalyah’s son Yeshayah and seventy \add other\add* men,
\li1
\v 8 from the descendants of Shefatyah: Mikael’s son Zevadyah and eighty \add other\add* men;
\li1
\v 9 from the descendants of Yoav: Yehiel’s son Ovadyah and 218 \add other\add* men,
\li1
\v 10 from the descendants of Shelomit: Yosifiah’s son and one hundred and sixty \add other\add* men,
\li1
\v 11 from the descendants of Bevai: his son Zekaryah and twenty-eight \add other\add* men,
\li1
\v 12 from the descendants of Azgad: Hakkatan’s son Yohanan and one hundred and ten \add other\add* men,
\li1
\v 13 from the later descendants of Adonikam: Elifelet, Yeiel, and Shemayah, and sixty \add other\add* men,
\li1
\v 14 and from the descendants of Bigvai: Utai and Zakkur and seventy \add other\add* men.
\s1 Ezra finds some Levites to take
\p
\v 15 \add Firstly,\add* I gathered them \add near\add* the river that goes to Ahava, and we camped there for three days. I \add interviewed\add* the people and the priests and \add discovered that we didn’t have any Levites included\add* \add in the group\add*.
\v 16 \add So I summoned\add* the following leaders: Eliezer, Ariel, Shemayah, Elnatan, Yarib, \add a second\add* Elnatan, Natan, Zekaryah, and Meshullam, as well as the wise men: Yoyariv and \add a third\add* Elnatan.
\v 17 I commanded them to go to Iddo, the leader at Kasifya, and I \add told them to tell\add* Iddo and his relatives (temple servants in Kasifya) to send us \add some Levites\add* who would \add go to Yerushalem to\add* serve in our God’s \add temple\add*.
\v 18 \add Then since we had God’s favour\add*, they sent us a \add talented\add* man (from the sons of Mahli, son of Levi, son of Israel) and eighteen of his sons and \add other relatives\add*.
\v 19 \add They also sent\add* Hashavyah and Yeshayah (from Merari’s sons), and their relatives and sons—some twenty men—
\v 20 plus two hundred and twenty \add descendants of\add* Levite temple servants that \add King\add* David and his officials had appointed for service—all designated by name.
\s1 Ezra’s fasting and praying
\p
\v 21 Then \add right\add* there by the river Ahava, I proclaimed a fast to humble ourselves \add in front of\add* our God to \add request that he’d smooth the\add* way \add ahead\add* for us, and for our children, and for all our property,
\v 22 because I was ashamed to request an army and horsemen from the king to help us from \add possible enemies\add* on the way. \add Also, you see,\add* we had \add previously\add* told the king, “Our God \add does\add* good to all those who \add honour\add* him, but his might and his \add anger\add* are against all those who abandon him.”
\v 23 \add So\add* we fasted and sought \add wisdom\add* from our God concerning this, and he \add listened to our requests\add*.
\s1 The gift and donations for the temple
\p
\v 24 Then I chose twelve of the leaders of the priests along with with Sherevyah and Hashavyah and ten of the other Levites,
\v 25 and \add as they watched,\add* I weighed out the gold and silver, and the \add valuable\add* utensils—the offering for the house of our God that the king, and his counsellors and officials, and all the \add exiled Israelis who could be contacted\add*, had offered.
\v 26 \add It came to\add* three tonnes of gold, twenty-one tonnes of silver, and another three tonnes of silver containers,
\v 27 as well as twenty gold bowls that weighed another eight kilograms, and two polished bronze containers that were as valuable as gold.
\p
\v 28 “You are sacred to Yahweh,” I told them all, “and the \add containers and utensils\add* are sacred, and the gold and silver are a freewill offering to Yahweh, the God of your ancestors.
\v 29 \add Look after them all carefully\add* until you weigh them out \add in front\add* of the leaders of the priests and Levites and the leaders of the Israeli elders in the chambers of Yahweh’s house in Yerushalem.”
\v 30 So the priests and the Levites \add accepted\add* the \add receipt\add* of the gold and silver, and the containers, to take them to Yerushalem—to the house of our God.
\s1 The return to Yerushalem
\p
\v 31 Then in mid-April, we set out from the river Ahava to go to Yerushalem, and \add we had God’s favour as he kept us safe from any enemies or ambushes\add* on the way.
\v 32 \add So\add* we arrived at Yerushalem, and \add rested\add* there for three days.
\v 33 On the fourth day, the gold and silver and the \add containers and utensils\add* were weighed out in the \add temple\add*—\add being handed over to\add* Uriyyah’s son Meremot, the priest, and with him was Pinhas’s son Eleazar (and with them were Yeshua’s son Yozavad, and Binnuy’s son Noadyah, the Levites).
\v 34 \add They recorded all the items with their weights\add*.
\p
\v 35 The \add descendants of the former captives who had returned from\add* exile offered burnt offerings to Israel’s God: twelve bulls for all Israel, 96 rams, 77 lambs, then twelve male goats for a sin offering. The whole was \add presented as\add* a burnt offering to Yahweh.
\v 36 They \add relayed\add* the king’s orders to the governors and officials of \add the province\add* beyond the river, and so they honoured the people and God’s house.
\c 9
\s1 The mourning of Ezra of pegkamasinupaken of Israelis
\p
\v 1 Now as soon as those things were finished, the leaders came to me, saying, “The people of Israel, and the priests and Levites have not separated themselves from the peoples of the lands according to their abominations, of the Canaanite, the Hittite, the Perizzite, the Jebusite, the Ammonite, the Moabite, the Egyptian, and the Amorite.
